{"name":"Personal Financing","id":162,"content":"<div class=\"math\">Income = \\color{red}{Expense} + \\color{pink}{Saving} + \\color{green}{Investment}</div>\n\n<p><strong>Investment</strong></p>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#7f8c8d;\">Why do companies sell stock/share?</span></p>\n\n<p>To raise money instead of going to banks companies sell <em><strong>shares/stocks</strong></em> or <strong><em>bonds</em></strong> in <strong><em>Capital&nbsp;Market</em></strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Common Stocks, Preferred Stocks</p>\n\n<div class=\"math\">\\color{blue}{Risk \\propto Return}</div>\n\n<p><strong>Growth Companies</strong>: Good startups.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Value Companies</strong>: Well established mature companies. Easier to evaluate risk.</p>\n\n<p>Warren Buffet has earned a lot using Value cmpanies, <em>hidden gems</em>. [[But now a days, is anything hidden??]]</p>\n\n<p>Market Cap: Small, Medium, Large d/o the number of shares (of company) being traded in market.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Blue Chip Companies</strong>: Well recognised leader companies. E.g. Coca-Cola, Pepsi, Microsoft.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<hr />\n<h2>Buying Stocks:</h2>\n\n<p>(Buying) For how long?</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">For long term: Look at their balance sheets, Income Statement, Cash Flow Statement, Expansion Plans etc. Company&#39;s profit should be upward, and should not have much liabilities.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">For short term: Look at Total and Avg. Daily Trading Volume, Price Movement, Kind of Volatility, Current Price relative to past 52-week high price or low price point. Some studies have found that prices are more likely to go up or down when the current price is near their 52-week high or low.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<hr />\n<h2>Taking advantage of Market Timing:</h2>\n\n<p>If you know about correlation b/w events e.g. price of oil and value of related companies, launch of new experimental drugs which are potentially going to be approved, video-games which can capture markets.</p>\n\n<p>You have to be on lookout, read a lot, grab the opportunity earlier. A perfect example would be BitCoin.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Selling Stocks:</p>\n\n<p><strong><em>Disposition Effect:</em></strong> Our propensity to sell our winners too soon and hang on to losers for too long. (General theory)</p>\n\n<p>How to deal with it? - Apply algorithm of your choice without emotions getting into the way.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Exchanges:</p>\n\n<p>Real and Virtual Exchanges.</p>\n\n<p>Few companies listed in all of the exchanges for a given country.</p>\n\n<p>Research says that (high trading) quality companies list in NYSE rather than NASDAQ. What&#39;s the equivalent for india?</p>\n\n<p>However, it is observed that only a few of companies which become eligible for NYSE actually choose to joing NYSE leaving NASDAQ. Why? - No satisfactory answer, but probably because most tech companies are listed on NASDAQ.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<hr />\n<h2>Mutual Funds:</h2>\n\n<p>See the manager of the fund.. is he doing this for long time or not?&nbsp;See how the fund performed in the time of financial crisis?&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;- PureEquity vs DynamicEquity</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;What kind of investment?<br />\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;-&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Does it help with IncomeTax saving?<br />\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;- Every investment option under 80C comes with lock-in period<br />\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;- You can claim max of 1.5 lakhs of investment tto be tax free (using any combination of options)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;- ELSS (Equity Linked Saving Schemes) ; LockInPeriod = 3+ yrs<br />\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;- Not mandatory to take money out after lock-in period</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>INDEX FUNDS:</p>\n\n<p>Are funds that are collection of other funds that represent the whole capital market in general. Basically when you invest in Index Funds, you are investing in the whole market altogether.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<hr />\n<h2>Insurance</h2>\n\n<p>Insurance is about protecting what you already have, in speculation of a risk which can take away what you have e.g. an accident, a costly medical operation, an illness etc.</p>\n\n<p>Insurance companies earn when they have more amount of money coming in as premiums than they have to pay in form of claims.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Insurance companies try to reduce the chances that they have to pay in form of claim by ensuring that they have correct information about your activities which possibly can lead you into risky situations. If youl lie about that information, it can be used by companies in court case to not pay your claim at all.</p>\n\n<p>By insuring diverse group of people and diverse categories of risks, companies reduce their chances to pay the claim.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2><span style=\"color:#3498db;\">TAX SAVING</span></h2>\n\n<p>80C Deductions in Tax: (max 1.5 lac)<br />\n&nbsp; &nbsp; By investment: PF, PPF, NSC, MF<br />\n&nbsp; &nbsp; By expenditure: Tution Fee, HomeLoan principle amount</p>\n\n<p>80D Deductions in Tax: 25k for mediclaim</p>\n\n<p>80CCD-1B Deductions: (max 50k)<br />\n&nbsp; &nbsp; NPS (National Pension Scheme) 9-11% return&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Section-24 Deduction: (max 2 lac) on House properties</p>\n\n<p>80E Deduction: ()<br />\n&nbsp; &nbsp; Education Loan for education inside india only</p>\n\n<p><br />\nHRA, MedA, TravelA<br />\n13A min(50% of basic salary, HRA, RentPaid - 10% of basic salary) is tax free</p>\n\n<p>80GG Deduction: ( max 60k )<br />\n&nbsp; &nbsp; In case no HRA component in salary</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2><font color=\"#3498db\">INCOME TAX RETURN</font></h2>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2><span style=\"color:#2980b9;\">TECHNICAL ANALYSIS</span></h2>\n\n<p><a data-saferedirecturl=\"https://www.google.com/url?q=https://www.etftrends.com/fixed-i